<title></title><BODY BACKGROUND="../gfx/bground.jpg"><PRE>
Date: Wed, 19 Jul 95 07:48:21 EDT
From: incident@vita.org (Disaster Information Administrator)
To: event@vita.org
Subject: Bangladesh: Floods  DHA-08


                              BANGLADESH-FLOODS
                     DHA-GENEVA INFORMATION REPORT NO.8
                                19 JULY 1995


  SITUATION

  1.      THE  OVERALL  SITUATION  IN  THE  FLOODED  AREA  AROUND THE
  BRAHMAPUTRA  BASIN (FROM CHILMARI TO ARICHA) HAS STARTED IMPROVING.
  THERE  HAS  BEEN  NO  INFORMATION  OF  INUNDATION  OF NEW AREA. THE
  RAINFALL  HAS  ALSO REDUCED SIGNIFICANTLY ALTHOUGH MONSOON IS QUITE
  ACTIVE.

  2.     IN THE GANGES BASIN, ALTHOUGH THE RISING TREND OF THE RIVERS
  HAS  SLOWED  DOWN AT ALL POINTS, THE SITUATION IN THE LOWER PART OF
  THE  BASIN  I.E. MUNSHIGANJ, MADARIPUR, SARIATPUR AND FARIDPUR WILL
  CONTINUE TO DETERIORATE SLOWLY AND NO IMPROVEMENT IS EXPECTED SOON.

  3.      IN  THE  MEGHNA  BASIN, THE SITUATION IN THE LOWER PART MAY
  DETERIORATE  FURTHER  IN  THE  NEXT  FEW  DAYS.  NEW  AREAS  MAY BE
  INUNDATED  IN  COMILLA,  NARSHINGDI AND BRAHMANBARIA DISTRICTS. THE
  OVERALL SITUATION MAY START IMPROVING WITHIN NEXT 3-4 DAYS PROVIDED
  NO INCESSANT RAIN OCCURS.

  4.      NEW AREAS OF THE CAPITAL DHAKA AND ITS ADJOINING AREAS LIKE
  NARAYANGANJ  AND  SAVAR  HAVE  BEEN  ENGULFED BY FLOOD WATER AS THE
  WATER  LEVEL  OF  BURIGANGA AT DHAKA, TURAG AT MIRPUR, KALIGANGA AT
  TARAGHAT  AND  KALIGANJ/DHALESHWARI AT NARIANGANJ ARE FLOWING ABOVE
  DANGER  LEVEL.  THIS  IS DUE TO PASSING OF EXCESSIVE WATER FROM THE
  UPPER   BRAHMAPUTRA  TOWARDS  THE  DOWNSTREAM.  THE  INCREASE  WILL
  CONTINUE FOR THE NEXT 2-3 DAYS THUS FURTHER INUNDATING NEW AREAS.

  5.      THE  UPDATED  DAMAGE  REPORT  (AS  OF  0800 HRS OF 17 JULY)
  RECEIVED  FROM  THE  EMERGENCY  OPERATION CENTRE OF THE MINISTRY OF
  DISASTER   MANAGEMENT  AND  RELIEF/DISASTER  MANAGEMENT  BUREAU  IS
  PROVIDED  AS  FOLLOWS:   TOTAL  NUMBER  OF  DISTRICTS AFFECTED:  34
  (INCLUDING  2  MUNICIPALITIES);   TOTAL  NUMBER OF THANAS AFFECTED:
  195;  TOTAL  NUMBER OF FAMILIES AFFECTED:  2,202,381;  TOTAL NUMBER
  OF  POPULATION  AFFECTED:   12,625,006;  CROPS DAMAGED:  (A) FULLY:
  908,068 ACRES AND (B) PARTLY:  847,849 ACRES;  HOUSES DAMAGED:  (A)
  FULLY: 207,843 AND (B) PARTLY:  732,174;  TOTAL DEATHS:  66;  TOTAL
  DEATH OF CATTLE:  9,819;  DAMAGED TO EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTIONS:  (A)
  FULLY:   364  AND  (B)  PARTLY:   2,796;  ROAD DAMAGED:  (A) FULLY:
  2,546  KMS  AND  (B) PARTLY:  12,919 KMS;  EMBANKMENT DAMAGED:  596
  KMS;  AND CULVERTS DAMAGED:  1,325.

  5.     THE UNITED NATIONS DISASTER MANAGEMENT TEAM, IN THE PRESENCE
  OF  EXPERTS  FROM  THE BANGLADESH METEOROLOGICAL DEPARTMENT AND THE
  FLOOD   FORECASTING   AND  WARNING  CENTRE,  REVIEWED  THE  OVERALL
  SITUATION.  IT  WAS  STATED THAT THE EARLY FLOODS IN THE MEGHNA AND
  BRAHMAPUTRA BASIN WERE THE RESULTS OF HEAVIER THAN NORMAL MONSOONAL
  RAIN  ALL  OVER  THESE  BASINS  COMBINED  WITH ONRUSH OF WATER FROM
  INDIA. THE GANGES BASIN (RAJSHAHI DIVISION) WILL EXPERIENCE SIMILAR
  RAINFALL  IN  NEXT 3-4 WEEKS. CONSIDERING THE RAINFALL DISTRIBUTION
  PATTERN,  IT WAS PREDICTED THAT THERE MIGHT BE A SYNCHRONIZATION OF
  BRAHMAPUTRA AND GANGES FOR A SHORT DURATION BUT ITS CONSEQUENCE MAY
  NOT BE SO DISASTROUS.

  NATIONAL RESPONSE

  6.      THE  GOVERNMENT  HAS FURTHER INCREASED THE SUPPLY OF RELIEF
  ASSISTANCE  THROUGH THE MINISTRY OF DISASTER MANAGEMENT AND RELIEF.
  NGOS  (PARTICULARLY CARE, RDRS, MSF) AND UN AGENCIES (MAINLY UNICEF
  AND WHO) HAVE ALSO GEARED UP ASSISTANCE.

  7.     THE OVERALL HEALTH SITUATION IS NOT ALARMING AND NO OUTBREAK
  OF  DIARRHOEA/MALARIA HAS BEEN REPORTED BY WHO  OTHER THAN SPORADIC
  OCCURRENCES.  WHO  HAS INCREASED THE SUPPLY OF ORS, WATER PURIFYING
  TABLETS  AND BLEACHING POWDER. ADDITIONAL 5 MILLION WATER PURIFYING
  TABLETS HAVE BEEN ORDERED BY WHO.

  8.      THE ASSOCIATION FOR DEVELOPMENT AGENCIES (ADAB) HAS MADE AN
  ASSESSMENT OF THE OVERALL SITUATION. ON THE BASIS OF THE REPORTS OF
  ASSESSMENT,  RELIEF  DISTRIBUTION  WORKS  HAVE BEEN ASSIGNED TO THE
  NGOS  WORKING  UNDER  ADAB  AUSPICES.  IN  ITS  ROLE  AS  THE  MAIN
  COORDINATOR,  ADAB  IS  EXPECTED  TO  FURTHER  REVIEW THE SITUATION
  SHORTLY.

  7.      AS  YET,  NO  REQUEST FOR INTERNATIONAL ASSISTANCE FROM THE
  GOVERNMENT  HAS  BEEN  RECEIVED.  DHA/UNDP  RESIDENT REPRESENTATIVE
  CONTINUES TO MONITOR SITUATION.


  TELEPHONE NO.  +41-22-917-1234
  IN CASE OF EMERGENCY ONLY:  TELEPHONE NO.  +41-22-917-2010
  DESK   OFFICER:    MR.   Y.   FUKASAWA,    DIRECT   TELEPHONE   NO.
  +41-22-917-3131
  PRESS    TO   CONTACT:   MS.   M.   MOULIN-ACEVEDO,   DIRECT   TEL.
  +41-22--917-2856
  TELEX:  414242 DHA CH

                   = DEPARTMENT OF HUMANITARIAN AFFAIRS +



