<DOCHDR>
http://www.travelleader.com:80/tl.html 204.249.214.30 19970118213656 text/html 18005
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 18 Jan 1997 21:35:56 GMT
Server: Apache/1.0.0
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 17833
Last-modified: Sun, 03 Nov 1996 21:36:29 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>TL Page</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><CENTER><IMG SRC="tllogo.gif" WIDTH="225" HEIGHT="54" ALIGN=bottomNATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><br><I>A consumer newsletter providing information and ideas for travelers.<BR>Discussed here are sources of travel services and information; noteworthy<BR>developments at destinations and resorts, various air and ground transportation<BR>modes, on unusual cruises and tours; ways to save money, etc.</I></center><p><b><a href="mailto:dnesbett@travelleader.com">DANesbett, Editor</a></b><p><center><font size=+2><a name="top">Contents</a></font><p></center><a href="#cruising">Cruising by RV Along the Outer Banks</a><p><a href="#lookat">Look at Where You Are Going</a><p><a href="#finding">Finding Your Best Vacation Package</a><p><a href="#thecarib">The Caribbean Vacation Planner</a><hr><font size=+2><a name="cruising">Cruising by RV Along the Outer Banks</a></font><p>Cape Hatteras is known as "The Graveyard of the Atlantic" because it has been the doom of many skilled navigators over the centuries. In the hope of saving hours if not days of sailing, they have given the infamous cape too little respect and too narrow a berth. The villain was, as it still is, the confluence here of the Gulf Stream and other currents to produce unchartable tides, shifting sandbars, fickle winds and some unpredictable weather. A conspiring of these elements often left vessels foundering helplessly on the shoals. Shipwrecks were so common that the U.S. Lifesaving Service's twenty-five stations on the Outer Banks, which operated well into this century when the U.S. Coast Guard took over, were a significant local employer. Daring rescues in foul weather via lifeboats propelled by human muscle, or in "breeches buoys" dangled on ropes extended from ship to shore over white-capped waves, were among the most widely known heroic deeds of their day. <p>North Carolina's Outer Banks stretch from the Virginia border to the tip of Ocracoke Island,120 miles south along the North Carolina Coast, with Hatteras Lighthouse both its symbolic and geographical center. We elected to make this passsage on land, however, our first venture in a motor home... We can care less if our blue water sailing friends are disdainful. The land cruise is infinitely safer than making the passage "outside," while allowing more activities and points of interest along the way than going by boat "inside" the cape.  <p>This maritime highway "North Carolina Route 12" on which we travel often is within sight of both the ocean and Pamilco Sound, that great protected sea that hosts the Inland Waterway here and defines over half of North Carolina's mainland coast. During nor'easters and hurricanes, the road itself often is endangered, if not temporarily closed, by driving ocean spray or drifts of sand. Conversely, a storm coming out of the southwest off of Pamlico Sound, such as it did this past March, can cause flooding that plays equal havoc.<p>Traveling down and then back up Route 12 in our self-contained cruiser, we are able to stop and walk on some of the miles of beaches between Nags Head and Ocracoke Village. During our sojourns, we listen to the seductive drawl of native accents, some with an occasional hint of Elizebethan inflections, develop an almost intimate relationship with the local wildlife, maintain our independence from motels and restaurants unless one of them totally excites our fancy, and follow our impulse at any moment to move our lodging to a new location. To say we are enjoying a moveable feast only begins to describe our trip; we have our own moveable resort that keeps us close to the whole seashore experience which is the reason we have come .(More)<p>Furthermore, the symbiosis between our chosen destination and mode of transportation plays itself out in many ways during the course of the trip. The informality of the Outer Banks is complemented by the RV (for recreational vehicle) lifestyle, which is equally casual. <p>In our travels we see many kinds of RVs, from tent trailers and vans, to travel trailers and motorhomes. At campgrounds, one experiences a cross section of America from senior executives to postal workers. If there is a snobbery, it is that there is none. If a politician wants to take the pulse of middle America, this is where to come.<p>Many we talk to in the campgrounds have traveled throughout North America, with the kids when younger, and then as older "empty nesters", are visiting offspring and grandchildren in their homes far-flung around the county. In between they may spend time in New Orleans or Yellowstone. One couple, with grown children now living on both coasts, has visited all 49 U.S. states on the North American continent, and has toured extensively in Canada and Mexico.<p>Many coming to the Outer Banks have brought their surf casting rods. With the bluefish running, they do not hesitate to share their catch with us. <p>The demographic mix of people here shifts according to season, depending upon whether or not schools are in session. The off-season is more peaceful at the campgrounds and on the beaches. Once schools let out, the ratios shift from predominantly seniors and retirees, to at least an even split of families with children, a population segment that is growing as the maturing the baby boomer generation moves into the family-rearing years. Whether staying in an RV or a tent, camping is a shared family experience that most enjoy and can afford. <p>We note a heightened camaraderie among RVers in the private KOAs (for Kampgrounds of America).  Camping and being with other campers here is an activity unto itself. The $15-25 overnight fee reflects that one can get a "full hookup" for electrical power, potable water and sewage, as well as have access to a campgrounds store, game room, and swimming pool  these latter amenities assuming greater importance once schools are out. The KOA campground at Chesapeake, Virginia, en route here, even offers pony rides.<p>Our neighbor's attitude at the KOA in Rodanthe, where we stay our first night on Hatteras Island, about our going on to outlying Ocracoke Island, is, "Why go there? There's nothing to do." <p>That sounds so good to us that we immediately head for the ferry. And how right he was. It is semi-desolation and total bliss. <p>At the National Parks Camground on Ocracoke Island, like the others elsewhere throughout the United States, there is no hookup. Little matter: we are in a totally self-sufficient vehicle with holding tanks, an auxillary generator and extra batteries. Furthermore, the nightly fee here is only $11.00, $5.50 for seniors (over 62.) Here also are people with just tents or tent trailers, seeking a purer camping experience.<p>At Ocracoke we pick our spot alone near a sand dune and turn off the motor. The roar of the ocean, less than 200 yards away, lulls us to sleep this night. During the following days a short hike across the dune brings us to the broad beach where we find a few fishermen, a half dozen varieties of shore birds and an occasional four wheel drive vehicle cruising past with its surf casting rods standing smartly upright in a row across the front bumper. Driving on the beach is such a part of the local tradtion that the Park Service allows it here, whereas it does not, for example, on Cape Cod. <p>We observe individuals and couples arriving, pitching a tent, disappearing within,  appearing the next morning to walk the beach, then striking the tent and leaving.  New York and New Jersey license plates indicate a full day's drive to get here. Pale and wan-looking upon arrival, we wonder what pressures at home has made them come all of this distance. One young man in his late twenties traveling and fishing alone tells us he just had to escape from the office for a few days. Apparently the word is out about the cure from civilization offered here.<p>One thing that these people also must have discovered is that the National Park Service Campgounds are a treasure in themselves, as are the people who run them.. The areas are thoughtfully layed out providing maximum individual space  mowed, clipped and immaculately maintained, with rarely the blemish of even a piece of paper on the ground. The Parks Service personnel, in their squared-off ranger's hats, always seem in command of their jobs and eager to help guests. One guide explains that The Cape Hatteras National Seashore, over 75 miles long and covering over 30,000 acres, contains three other active campsites in addition to this one at Ocracoke. The northernmost is at Oregon Inlet. Frisco and Cape Point are near the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse. A fourth one at Salvo is temporarily closed due to government budget restrictions. <p>The Park Service offers self-guided "interpretive tours." We walk over a trail of pine straw onto a gray, weathered catwalk that takes us through stands of salt hay into the heart of the salt marsh.  The rich environment of the marsh, full of decayed vegetation in which mollusks and crustacia thrive, is descibed on a trailside placard as "organic soup." An interpretive trail indeed! Bushes are pointed out that protect themselves from the damage of salt spray by keeping their maximum growth lower than the level of the dunes.<p>At the Pea Island Nature Preserve forty miles farther north near the Oregon Inlet Campground, to which we subsequently move,  we find spring-fed fresh water ponds that support river otters and muskrats, swimming and playing with little apparent regard for our presence. In the salt water ponds and marshes blue herons and snowy egrets dance in the mirkey water to stir up their dinner. While viewing all of this in clear sunshine from a raised observation platform, a thunderstorm progressing up the Banks from Cape Hatteras provides a brilliant rainbow. The whole vast scene, with all of its colors and life,.scans like a Frederic Church painting, too grand in its scope to be real.<p>With storms constantly coming and going, so does the shoreline.  Oregon Inlet is a major outlet from Pamlico Sound into the ocean, used daily by sports fishermen, and is a lifeline for the commercial fishing fleet docking at Wachese on Roanoke Island. There is a school of thought that argues to leave the seashore alone to shift sand and move inlets as it pleases. It always has and it always will. The inlet that allowed Sir Walter Raleigh's vessel to penetrate the Outer Banks in 1584 to Albemarle Sound and to found its colony on Roanoke Island (now known as the "Lost Colony"), no longer exists, closed centuries ago by the sea's action.  Likewise Oregon Inlet, the present-day principal break in the Banks, did not exist at all until it was opened by storms in 1846. <p>Now man manages nature here at the inlet and at other places along this seashore because his interests are threatened. Heroic measures are being used to save the channel from filling in. The battle is endless.<p>Likewise, we see the mammoth sandbags and breakwaters built to save the 208-foot tall Hatteras Lighthouse, which when erected in 1870, was 1,500 feet from the ocean, but which  now is protected by only 200 feet of headland.  While still a functioning lighthouse and the tallest one in North America, it is also the leading symbol of the Outer Banks and a major tourist attraction. Every possible measure is being used to save it.<p>In our RV we drive to the field where on December 17, 1903 the Wright Brothers made their historic first powered flight . Next we go to see the spectacular Elizabethan Gardens on nearby Roanoke Island, where the Lost Colony is immortalized in the grand operatic pageant performed each year. But then it starts to rain, hard at times. We have lunch in the RV, take time out for a siesta, and because it is still raining, decide not to return to our campground at Oregon Inlet. We will quit while we are ahead after almost a week of near-perfect weather. With no need to go back to a hotel to check out, and with all our belongings on board, we turn on the engine and head towards home. Life these past few days has been just as simple and unplanned as that.<p>If you plan to go there, According to an industry spokesperson, the total cost to rent an RV averages $1,000-1,2000 per week, but prices vary greatly depending upon vehicle size, season and location. . The largest national renter is Cruise America, which operates in over 100 locations throughout the U.S., including Washington, D.C., and Raleigh, North Carolina, their closest to the Hatteras area. For more detailed information and reservations through Cruise America, which also offers fly-drive programs and the option of dropping the vehicle in a second location, call 800-327-7799, or a travel agent. <p>For a copy of the Recreation Vehicle Rental Association directory, which lists over 200 dealers nationwide, plus a copy of their 32-page booklet Rental Ventures, call 800-336-0355. There is a $7.50 charge and major credit cards are accepted.<p>First time RV renters should allow at least two hours to get checked out on their vehicles and to provision. <p>During holiday or vacation periods, campground reservations are recommended. The National Park Service 800-number is 365-CAMP, with reservations and advance payment accepted over the phone via a major credit card for certain campgrounds up to eight weeks in advance.. Seniors (62 years old) should so specify when making their reservation to receive the 50% discount.<p>Several comprehensive camping directories also are available, including the 1,750-page Woodall's Campground Directory , providing telephone numbers for virtually all for public and private campgrounds worth considering (and some that are not), and AAA Campbooks in 11 regional editions A KOA directory, which includes maps, rates, facilities available at each of their 550 locations and their phone numbers for reservations, is free at any of their campgrounds, or by sending  $3.00 to KOA, P.O.Box 30558, Billings, Montana 59114. <p>Visitor information also can be obtained from the North Carolina Division of Travel & Tourism by calling 800-VISIT NC. For a literate and entertaining account of the history, people and ecology of the area, told as a narrative of the author's visit there, read Anthony Bailey's The Outer Banks, published by Farrar, Straus and Giroux, New York, in 1989.<br><a href="#top"><img src="up.gif" border=0 alt="Up"></a><hr><font size=+2><a name="lookat">Look at Where You Are Going</a></font><br>For travelers who would like to see where they might be going before they go there, Destinations on Tape may be their answer. Islands, countries, cities, cruise lines, tour operators, hotels, etc., supply the tapes, so they naturally tend to be promotional in nature, but are generally informative and high in production quality. Full page ads promoting the service have appeared in The New York Times and Smithsonian magazine, among others.<p>The tapes you select are combined onto one customized video cassette. Each tape selected is priced at $7.00 and there is a per order handling and duplicating fee of $5.75. In other words, if you order three videos, say of Bermuda, Cambridge Beaches there, and the Southampton Princess hotel, the total comes to $26.75. Second day air also is available. For a free catalog, or to place orders with credit card by phone, call 800-822-4604. The e-mail address is govideo@aol.com.<br><a href="#top"><img src="up.gif" border=0 alt="Up"></a><hr><font size=+2><a name="finding">Finding Your Best Vacation Package</a></font><br>A travel agent we know already has done a lot of the homework for you. He is Arthur Mehmel of Darien, Connecticut, whose clients come to him from all over the country. This is because Arthur, who specializes in the Caribbean, has assiduously combed all of the tour catalogs, entered rates for comparable service levels and rooms into his computer, and come up with the best price for any hotel or resort in any given destination. <p>His company names say it all: either The Caribbean Travel Service or TourScan. Either will do, since both are the exact same office. Says syndicated columnist and travel guidebook guru Arthur Frommer (see above), "Mehmel deftly extracted the best package values in dozens of categories....These he then printed in a sprightly 52 page catalog that I personally find a delight to peruse, in addition to its being the most systematic, scientific exposure of travel marketing practices in all the industry." Similarly salutary reviews have appeared in Caribbean Travel & Life  magazine, Playboy , Birnbaum's Caribbean, and the latest Fielding's Guide to the Caribbean.<p>For more information call 800 962 2080 or 203 655 8091. The e-mail address is tourscan@netcom.com(.)<br><a href="#top"><img src="up.gif" border=0 alt="Up"></a><hr><font size=+2><a name="thecarib">The Caribbean Vacation Planner</a></font><br>The Caribbean Vacation Planner is another useful resource for those contemplating an island vacation, and it's  free.This 270-page directory profiles each island destination, contains a calendar of special events, a chart of available activities according to island, and is crammed with color photos and maps. It also contains  articles by travel authorities about sports, ecology, history, the arts, shopping, and foods. Published by  the Caribbean Coalition for Tourism, The Caribbean Vacation Planner is available free by calling 1-800-356-9999 x 341.<br><a href="#top"><img src="up.gif" border=0 alt="Up"></a><hr><center><a href="http://www.travelleader.com/butbar2.map"><IMG SRC="http://www.travelleader.com/tlsbutbr.gif" ISMAP border=0 WIDTH="390" HEIGHT="78" ALIGN=bottom></a></center></body></html>
