<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>TML Page</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><CENTER><IMG SRC="tmllogo.gif" WIDTH="225" HEIGHT="54" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR><I>For travel industry executives, an industry newsletter of views, issuesand trends. <BR>It also contains a listing of major industry meetings, as well as changesin <BR>key executive, advertising and public relations agency assignments. </I></CENTER><P><B><A HREF="mailto:dnesbett@travelleader.com">DANesbett, Editor</A></B><BR><P><CENTER><FONT size=+2><A NAME="top"></A>Contents</FONT></CENTER><P><A HREF="#malls">And the Winner is... Outlet Malls</A> <p><A HREF="#profitin">Profiting from Asian Growth</A> <p><A HREF="#concerns">Concerns About Safety Abroad</A> <p><A HREF="#avideois">A Video is Worth a Thousand Words</A> <p><A HREF="#marketin">Marketing Briefs:</A><br>Travel Industry Revenues<br>People magazine, Carnival & CLIA<p><A HREF="#whoson">"Who's on First?"</A><br>Changing of the Guard<p><A HREF="#adagency">Ad Agency Action</A><br>More Information Please<p><A HREF="calendar.htm">Calendar of Meetings & Events</A> <HR><FONT size=+2><ANAME="malls"></A>AND THE WINNER IS....OUTLET MALLS</FONT> <p>Even in comparison to the much touted pulling power of entertainment centers such as casino gambling, theme parks, regional and historic attractions, and live shows, the malls are pulling more visitors than all of these other attractions combined. <p>People not only love to shop, they have to shop to maintain today's designer-driven, dual income lifestyle. Who's got time to shop during week? It's got to be on vacation and on the weekend. <p>The first harbinger of this trend was seen over a decade ago when Freeport, Maine, home of L.L.Bean was the state's (it even said "Maine, Vacationland" on the license plates) second largest attraction for out of state tourists. The bargains galore, mostly close outs and discontinued items, could be had only by visiting the store, which often was crowded even at at midnight during the summer months. Imagine getting a pair of genuine L.L. Bean hiking boots for half price. <p>Growth of the malls has been nothing short of exponential in the decade of the nineties, however. With a 50% increase since l990 in the number of malls to 311, there has been a doubling in the number of shops. Moreover, mall developers look to the potential for tourist traffic in their planning. In the gigantic Potomac Mills mall outside of Washington, on third of the shoppers are tourists, many of them foreigners. At the 400-store Mall of America outside of Minneapolis, of the 40 million annual visitor count, 12.5 million of it is accounted for by tourists. Northwest Airlines, based in Minneapolis, with its strong Pacific franchise, brings in planeloads of Japanese. It also brings in shoppers from Los Angeles just for the day. <p>The resurgence in Hawaiian tourism is in no small way a result of the Japanese passion for buying American goods on American soil-at half the price they would pay in Japan. In 1995 the giant Waikele Factory Stores Mall in Waipahu drew almost one third of all Japanese visitors. The eastbound market, dominated by the Japanese, through April (1996) is 17.3% ahead of last year.Ironically, overextended Japanese real hotel developers are being bought out by Hawaiian and US-mainland real estate syndicates at one third the the original investment, who in turn will profit from the revitalized Japanese consumer economy. Bargains notwithstanding, like with many American households these days, a Tokyo working couple just does not have the time to shop at home. <p><br><a href="#top"><img src="up.gif" border=0 alt="Up"></a><hr><FONT size=+2><A NAME="profitin"></A>Profiting from Asian Growth</FONT><br>The Asian economic growth engine is expected to continue churning. Maybe not in the double digit range of the last decade, but certainly in the high single digit numbers. Anyone traveling in Asia only has to look at the abundance of construction cranes in Hong Kong, Singapore, China, Taiwan, Korea, Malaysia, etc. to believe this. <p>What we Westerners need to understand about doing business out there is how very important personal relationships are, and how they need to be carefully cultivated. Close to half of all business growth is controlled by the Chinese, both of mainland China and those living permanently overseas. It is a vast network of family, colleagues, and acquaintances that controls enormous wealth and provides an alternative to the kind of business institutions and services (including investment banks, lawyers, and accountants) more universally available in the West.. <p>John Naisbitt in his new book "Megatrends Asia: Profit or Peril" addresses the importance of the ethnic Chinese spread throughout the Far East in a decentralized business web. Likewise, so does author Jim Rohwer in &quot;Asia Rising: Why America Will Prosper as Asia's Economies Boom.&quot; The latter's central thesis is that more than offsetting the competition in labor and manufacturing to the West is the tremendous markets these rapidly developing economies of the East offer. Both books provide useful understanding to those of us seeking business partnerships and growth in this area. <p>In the more immediate future, US travel to China will be stimulated by people wanting to experience Hong Kong before the PRC takeover next year, and the Yangtze River, before the high dam changes the river's character forever, according to Simon Winchester, Asia-Pacific Editor of CN Traveler speaking at a PATA gathering in New York in February. <p>One question centers on whether the new Chinese bureaucracy will allow the former British Crown Colony to prosper as it has in the past. <p>Then, too, there is the possibility that Shanghai, which serves the more dynamic northern provinces, will eclipse Hong Kong as China's principal commercial hub and gateway to the West. <p>In short, Hong Kong may be experiencing its best days right now. <p>The Yangtze River dam project of the coming decade will displace whole villages, compromise the natural beauty of many parts of the river, and restrict its flow in others to limit navigation. So best see it now, many believe, tour operators included.<p><br><a href="#top"><img src="up.gif" border=0 alt="Up"></a><hr><FONT size=+2><A NAME="concerns"></A>Concerns About Safety Abroad</FONT><br>According to the Menlo Consulting Group's TravelStyles&reg; study, 8% of all outbound pleasure travelers feared for their safety at some time on their last international trip, and 3% were victims of some criminal act. This translates to 2.4 million persons who were in fear, and 900,000 who actually were victimized. Since these are averages for all foreign-traveling Americans, some countries were much higher. Furthermore, these incidence levels can be multiplied many times in terms of their influence on potential travel, due to victims' expression of displeasure to their friends upon returning home-not to mention when the press prints any of this kind of bad news. <p>The problem also is that Americans have a low level of awareness of what goes on abroad, and of geography. &quot;The Troubles&quot; in Northern Ireland mean cancellations for Dublin, for example. People getting shot in a restaurant in St. Thomas has a ripple effect for tourism throughout the Caribbean. <p>The violent crimes three years ago in Florida prompted cancellations en masse from Europe, and the state was still suffering for it when another such incident occurred this year. One can be philosophical that shootings, robberies, and other unpleasantries have always happened to travelers. But this is serious business today, because relative safe destination alternatives are readily available, and those with unsafe images lose out...big time! <p><br><a href="#top"><img src="up.gif" border=0 alt="Up"></a><hr><p><FONT size=+2><A NAME="avideois"></A>A Video is Worth a Thousand Words</FONT><br>Kerry Cannon's Destinations on Tape, on the other hand, distributes videos for travel suppliers. Twice each year the catalog is mailed to 1.2 million US households with high leisure travel potential. Each supplier listing, with color logo and descriptive copy of the product, is priced at $1,975. There is virtually no other expense or effort on the part of the supplier since the consumer pays the cost of duplicating and shipping the tapes ordered. Each participating supplier then receives a list of those consumers ordering its tape-certainly a well-qualified group since each tape costs $7.00. (See our consumer letter The Travel Leader for further description of the service.) For more information call Destinations on Tape at 800-822-4604. The e-mail address is govideo@aol.com.<p><br><a href="#top"><img src="up.gif" border=0 alt="Up"></a><hr><p><FONT size=+2><A NAME="marketin"></A>Marketing Briefs</FONT><br>Selling Canada Becomes More of a State of Mind...and Money Canada's tourism industry is recognizing the importance of tourism with its check book. The new (February; 1995) Canadian Tourism Commission (CTC), a governmentally chartered private-public corporation replaces the old government agency, Tourism Canada. Now with a lot of help from its friends in the private sector, Canada has an annual promotion budget of $100 million. According to Tom Penney, the CTC's marketing director for the US, over $34 million of the funds this year have been allocated in media advertising and promotion towards developing this market...and are pretty much already spent in anticipation of the summer season. <p>Advertising emphasis is concentrated in New York, Chicago, and LA, to enable the14-week TV program, begun in February, to achieve effective impact. This means that the campaign's 250/week rating point level is strong enough to be heard above all the clutter and clatter on the tube. (And if you cannot afford that level in a major market, TML's experience says, don't even bother being there on TV.) <p>At the same time, the promise and tone of the commercials should get attention. Sophisticated urban charm and spectacular natural settings come alive with people kissing and whales breaching. Very nice! No need to know, therefore, whether the action is in Vancouver or in Montreal, in the Bay of Fundy or on the coast of British Columbia, which allows for a unified national campaign. The theme is "The World Needs More Canada" The campaign is extended with inserts in upscale magazines such as The New Yorker, Gourmet, and Travel & Leisure. Vickers & Benson, Toronto, is the advertising agency. <p>The promotion does not let us Yanks forget that the US dollar goes one-third further in Canada than at home. Also there is the new "Open Skies" agreement with the US, which means that the airlines from both the US and Canada are virtually unrestricted in their bilateral route expansions. Air Canada alone since February 1995 has added more than 30 new routes between the US and Canada. <p><FONT size=+2>People Magazine's Victories at Sea</FONT><br>There is no mystery about People magazine's ability to efficiently reach travelers of just about any stripe. The problem is, the efficiency only works with national buys in the magazine, and who's got that kind of money in the travel industry? The answer is Carnival Cruise Lines, the largest in the world. From Carnival's perspective the magazine's extensive reach can attract first time cruisers (only 2% of the US population has ever set foot on a cruise ship) in great quantities. From People magazine's perspective, this is the largest exclusive media buy in the history of the magazine. McFarland and Drier, Miami, is the ad agency. <p>This comes on the heals of the Cruise Lines International Association's (CLIA) 24-page People magazine insert on February 12. Replies are coming in at a rate four times greater than last year, according to Jim Godsman, CLIA's president. CN Traveler magazine also was a part of this "National Cruise Vacation Month" promotional program that includes a sweepstakes driving consumers to travel agencies, which as we all know, make over 95% of all cruise booking. <p><br><a href="#top"><img src="up.gif" border=0 alt="Up"></a><hr><FONT size=+2><A NAME="whoson"></A>Who's On First?</FONT><br><B>MUSICAL CHAIRS AT THE TOP CRUISE LINES Adam Aron</B> has resigned as chairman and CEO of Norwegian Cruise Line (NCL). He has been named to the same post at Vail Resorts Inc. which operated Vail and Beaver Creek ski resorts in Colorado. A Harvard &quot;B School&quot; alum, his travel industry career has been marked by highly innovative marketing programs, including the frequent flyer plan at PanAm, champaign flights for Western Airlines, and later a range of imaginative merchandising at Hyatt. <p><B>Bruce Nierenberg</B>, also a marketing innovator, becomes EVP at NCL where he started his career in the cruise industry. A pioneer in the concept of family cruising, he went on to found Premiere Cruise Lines and, with Costa, American Family Cruises, which Costa folded after eight months of operation. <p><B>Rod McLeod</B>, who had resigned precipitously as EVP of Royal Caribbean Cruise Line (RCCL), will assume the same title July 1, when his contractual &quot;non-compete&quot; clause expires, at Carnival, reporting to his old industry colleague and rival <B>Bob Dickson</B>, the line's president.. The four marketing vice presidents under McLeod at RCCL (Mike Applebaum, sales; Adam Goldstein, marketing; Margarita Navarrete, passenger services; and Brian Rice, market planning and development) now will report directly to the line's president <B>Richard Fein</B>. <p><B>Peter Ward</B>, former Rolls Rolls-Royce Motor Cars head brought in by Trafalgar House to run Cunard prior to its being sold to Norway's Kvaerner Plc., has resigned. For the moment his reorganization and marketing programs remain in place. He is being replace by <B>Antti Pankakoski</B>, a lawyer and head of Kvaerner's shipbuilding operation. Some speculate that the line is being dressed up to be sold off piecemeal. <p><B>OTHER CHANGINGS OF THE GUARD</B> <br><B>George Her</B>n has retired as vp/public relations at the French Government Tourist Office. George's career spans over three decades at Air France and at the FGTO, where he also supervised the advertising and promotional programs. He will continue to do independent communications consulting. He can be reached in New York City at 212 751 5311; in Palm Beach, Florida, at 407 844 0424. <p><B>Kenneth Hine</B> is retiring as president and CEO of the American Hotel & Motel Association (AH&amp;MA), where he has served for 27 years. He was inducted into the Travel Industry Association's Hall of Leaders at the TIA's annual conference on October 17. <p><B>William Fisher</B> has replaced Hine at AH&amp;MA. Fisher comes from a similar post at the National Restaurant Association (NRA)where he is credited with creating an educational foundation, with having intensified the organization's government affairs efforts in Washington, and with restructuring the NRA's financial and administrative activities. He also lectured and was an assistant professor at the Cornell Hotel School, from which he holds undergraduate and advanced degrees. <p><B>Antonio Enriques Savignac</B> for personal reasons has stepped down effective September 1 as Secretary-General of the World Tourism Organization(WTO) headquartered in Madrid, saying that the job is an exhausting one and that he didn't feel he was able to handle the required pace any longer. He has held the post for the past six and a half years, traveling incessantly for the organization during that period. Savignac, as you may remember, is the former Secretary of Tourism for Mexico, and earlier, while head of FONATUR, was in charge of developing the now highly successful resorts of Cancun and Ixtapa. He is returning to Mexico where he plans to remain active in teaching and writing about matters relating to tourism. <p><B>Francesco Frangialli</B>, deputy secretary-general, takes over Savignac's duties on an interim basis until a new secretary-general is elected and installed January 1, 1998. In spite of the US's decision, as part of its privatization posture to which the US Travel and Tourism Administration (USTTA) recently succumbed, to resign and withhold its $500,000 annual dues, Fragialli says that the WTO &quot;is in good shape, we have the respect of our members and are in a healthy financial situation....&quot; Savignac is generally credited with a large share of this success. <p><br><a href="#top"><img src="up.gif" border=0 alt="Up"></a><hr><FONT size=+2><A NAME="marketin"></A><B>MARKETING BRIEFS</B></FONT><br><B>T&L AND TW STILL TOP MEDIA GUNS</B> <br>Revenues for magazines in the travel classification increased 8% last year, according to Ad Age, more than keeping pace with the top revenue earners, newsweeklies, which gained 5.8%. <p>Travel & Leisure, the category's revenue leader, took in $85.5 million from circulation and ad sales. <p>Travel Weekly, the largest of the trades, realized $78.6 in revenues. to make it second overall in the travel publishing industry, consumer or trade. <p>The third most revenue-bearing book is Endless Vacation, a property of Resort Condominiums International, at $75.4 million. <p>Of ten business magazine classifications, travel is third behind computers and electronic engineering. TW, Travel Agent, and Tour & Travel News lead the trade category, which at $174 million, was 3.4% behind the previous year's revenue performance. <p><B>$5 BILLION TIMESHARE MARKET, ONCE THE UGLY DUCKLING OF LODGING, <br>NOW GETS PLENTY OF RESPECT </B><br>Back in the early eighties, when consumer abuse by the industry spawned a sleazy public image, annual sales were only $480 million. By the time the nineties were underway, however, the industry had cleaned itself up and had attracted operators such as Marriott, Hilton, ITT Sheraton and Disney. Their presence has played no small part in making timeshare the $5 billion industry it is today. <p>Another important factor has been the demographic growth of the family market. These increasing numbers of baby boomer parents are attracted to the opportunity for a familial bonding experience (until they've actually done it a couple of times), not to mention the seductive economics of being able to load the whole gang into a resort condo during vacations. <p>The company that dominated the industry's marketing then, as it does now, was Resort Condominiums International. Generally referred to in the trade simply as RCI, the company was founded by Christel DeHaan (with her ex husband). Now she is selling it to acquisitive-bent HFS, which under its chairman Henry Silverman, is constructing a deal that could be worth $825 million and puts her on the HFS board. Now that's a lot of respect. <p>Silverman, who only recently acquired Avis, sees RCI as part of a horizontal integration of travel facilities that includes 5,300 lodging franchises with names such as Days Inn, Howard Johnson, Ramada, Super 8, Knights Inn, Park Inn and Travelodge. <p>Now he will have a leading travel media outlet as well in which to tell his story. Endless Vacation magazine.<p><br><a href="#top"><img src="up.gif" border=0 alt="Up"></a><hr><FONT size=+2><A NAME="adagency"></A>AD AGENCY ACTION</FONT><br>Who can image Leo Burnett Chicago (creators of The Marlboro Man) without United Airlines (also creators of "Friendly Skies") after 31 years? The $100 million however has been reassigned to Fallon McElligott Minneapolis and Young & Rubicam of New York. Others in the running included the incumbent, plus Ammirati Puris Lintas, and TBWA Chiat/Day. <p>Fallon McElligott also handles Holiday Inn Worldwide, while in more than 40 countries Y&R handles Lufthansa, which has a marketing agreement with United. <p>Radisson Hospitality Worldwide, a division of the Carlson Companies, headquartered in Minneapolis, on the other hand, has chosen Ingalls advertising of Boston to handle its advertising account, estimated at $5-6 million. <p>The Greater Philadelphia Tourism Marketing Corp. account of $2 million goes to Tierney & Partners, Philadelphia, a division of True North Communications. <p><B>More Information Please</B><br><B>PATA Scrutinizes Region's Performance</B><br>"We are seeing a continued shift in the origin of travelers to the Pacific Asia region as a result of the growing economies of Asia," says Ms. Low Hoh Gek, Pacific Asia Travel Association (PATA) Director of Research. "With the emerging outbound markets of India, Indonesia and the People's Republic of China, this trend will be even more pronounced in future years." Asian travelers now account for 60.6% of the 36 PATA member nation arrivals up from 45.1% just a decade ago. Conversely, the share of arrivals from North America has declined during the period to 12.5% from 22.4%.<p>The overall increase for the PATA member destinations was up 9.1% last year, according to the organization's 125-page Annual Statistical Report, just released. It is available for a fee from PATA headquarters in San Francisco: Fax (415) 986-3458, phone: (415) 986-4646, e-mail: pata@class.org.<p><B>The ETC Looks Ahead</B><br>Meanwhile, the European Travel Commsiion (ETC) ponders whether the North American visitor count, running 5.3% ahead this year for a projected 9 million visitors in 1996, can be increased by one-third to 12 million departures by the year 2000, just four years from now, the kind of increase reminiscent of the early eighties. This is the question examined by speakers at the annual half-day marketing conference at New York's Grand Hyatt Hotel on Friday, November 8. For information call Donald N. Martin & Company at (212) 307-1200, fax (212) 307-1205 or e-mail at: dnmco@aol.com.<p><B>The Big Picture Sums it All Up</B><br>To read, or even to browse through the Travel Industry World Yearbook, The Big Picture 1995-96, makes us aware of how very much is happening globally in tourism, and how little we know. This 162-page volume proceeds from an overview and industry highlights, through the US states and foreign destination countries, to analyses by industry sectur (i.e. travel agents, hotels, airlines, etc.). Its text reflects the many years of active experience in the industry by the author, Somerset Waters, and the thoroughly professional editing job by former ASTA Travel News Editor Tom Bridges. The Big Picture is available for $79 plus $3 S&H ($11 foreign) from P.O. Box 610, Rye, NY 10580 or by calling (914) 921-0988.<p><br><a href="#top"><img src="up.gif" border=0 alt="Up"></a><hr><A HREF="http://www.travelleader.com/butbar2.map"><IMG SRC="http://www.travelleader.com/tlsbutbr.gif"ISMAP BORDER="0" WIDTH="390" HEIGHT="78" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></UL></BODY></HTML>
