<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE></TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><FONT size=+3><B>TIMELY NOTES FOR THE TRAVEL PRESS</B></FONT><BR><BR>November-December 1996 <P><CENTER></CENTER><P><FONT size=+1><B>INTERNET BECOMING A SIGNIFICANT INFORMATION RESOURCEFOR TRAVEL JOURNALIST...IN MORE WAYS THAN ONE</B></FONT><BR>The Society of American Travel Writers (SATW) has just completed a surveyto determine the level of Internet usage by its members. Tabulations revealthat roughly half of the respondents access the Internet on a regular basis.<BR><BR>In addition to the Web's being a valuable information resource, a numberof freelancers are auditing the sites of publications in which their &quot;hardcopy&quot; has appeared. They do so to ascertain whether there was any copyrightviolation....meaning whether or not additional royalties are due them forusing their work online. Heaven forbid that a publication might forget tomail a supplementary check. <P><CENTER></CENTER><P><FONT size=+1><B>TRAVEL JOURNALIST ORGANIZATIONS MERGE AND DIVERGE</B></FONT><BR>Don Bonhaus, US director of the World Federation of Travel Writers and Journalists(FIJET) tells us the organization currently is exploring opportunities toincrease its presence here, such as with the International Food, Wine & TravelWriters Association (IFW&amp;TWA). Such an expansion would add 450 journaliststo the 2,300+ members in 50 countries, where there also are 40 affiliateorganizations. FIJET was founded in 1954, and headquarters in Kortenberg,Belgium. <BR><BR>(FIJET Congress XXXIX October 23-30 in Mar Del Plata, Argentina, was themed,&quot;Internet, accessibility and opportunities for FIJET members.&quot;)<BR><BR>At the same time, the members of the Travel Journalist Guild (TJG) individuallyhave been invited to become members of FIJET. The Guild's membership isrestricted to 75 practicing professional (&quot;No clips, no trips&quot;)free lance writers. Membership slots are coveted. If you're thinking aboutapplying and wondering when there may be openings, start by reading obits.It's that tight. <BR><BR>The proposed merger between IFW&TA and NATJA, North American Travel JournalistsAssociation of 200 members, on the other hand, has been called off. NATJApresident and its newsletter writer Dan Schlossberg relates that insteadNATJA currently is focusing attention on an awards competition with prizesof three day weekends in several categories donated by Westin Hotels. <P><CENTER></CENTER><P><FONT size=+1><B><I>For more information...</I></B></FONT><BR>about travel press organizations, their activities and membership requirements,contact: <BR><BR><B>FIJET</B><BR>Don Bonhaus, US Director<BR>(World Federation of Travel Writers and Journalists)<BR>Tel: 908 291 2840 <BR>Fax: 908 291 9272 <BR><BR><B>IFW&amp;TWA</B><BR>Linda Marie Singer, Pres.<BR>Tel: 510 372 8805 <BR>(International Food, Wine & Travel Writers Association)<BR>E-Mail: lindamari@aol.com<BR>Ron Hodges, Exec.Dir.<BR>Tel: 310 433 5969<BR>E-Mail: medialpro@deltanet.com<BR><BR><B>NATJA</B><BR>Dan Schlossberg, Pres.<BR>(North American Travel Journalists Association)<BR>Tel: 201 791 3160<BR>Fax: 201 791 3349 <BR>E-Mail: 71574,3252@compuserve.com<BR><BR><B>NYTWA</B><BR>Tom Passavant, Pres<BR>(New York Travel Writers Association)<BR>Tel: 212 969 7517 <BR>Fax: 212 969 7557<BR><BR><B>SATW</B><BR>Susan Rexer, Admin. Coord'r<BR>(Society of American Travel Writers)<BR>Tel: 919 787 5181<BR>Fax: 919 787 4916<BR><BR><B>TJG</B><BR>Philip Hoffman, Exec. Sec.<BR>(Travel Journalist Guild)<BR>Tel: 312 664 9279 <BR>Fax: 312 664 9701<BR><P><CENTER></CENTER><P><FONT size=+1><B>THREE FOR THE MONEY</B></FONT><BR><B>1. ESCAPE</B> A new travel market on the block is Escape magazine, whichis focusing on adventure travel (try Bhutan, Outer Mongolia and North Korea).A charter issue free offer was mailed in September into high demo neighborhoods.Unsolicited manuscripts and photographs are welcome (with SASE), with noset payment scale established yet for either. The mailing address is POBox 5159, Santa Monica, CA 90409-5159. The phone there is 310 392 5235.<BR><BR><B>2. ADVENTURE TRAVEL BUSINESS</B> The fact that adventure travel really is on the leading edge these days is further exhibited by another publication entry, the trade spin off of Adventure West magazine, Adventure Travel Business. Its subjects cover conservation management and natural resources, marketing, trends, clients liability and risk management (people really do fall off of rocky cliffs and drown in raging rivers), doing business on The Internet, merchandising, etc. Queries can be emailed to editors@adv-media.com&gt; or mailed to PO Box 3210, Incline Village, NV 89450. <BR><BR>Best yet, visit the Adventure Travel Society site: <A HREF="http://www.adventurewest.com/">http://www.adventurewest.com</A>and get all of the needed addresses, editors' names and their individualemails, plus editorial and photo requirements and rates, paying up to $850for Adventure West stories. <BR><BR><B>3. GETAWAYS</B> The handsome premiere issue (250,000 copies) is out,edited by David Breul, formerly the editor of the late, and equally handsome,European Travel & Life. So far, the Getaways editors have bought only assignedstories, but unsolicited M/S's will be considered in the future, as wellas queries. Focus is on short, luxury vacation experiences in North America,which in addition to the US, Canada and Mexico, includes Hawaii and theCaribbean. The magazine's web site is <A HREF="http://www.getawaysmag.com/">http://www.getawaysmag.com</A>Send material to 95 Chestnut St , Providence, RI 02903. Phones (800) 2744549; (401) 421 2552; fax (401) 831 5624; and email at: getaways@getawaymag.com.<P><CENTER></CENTER><P><FONT size=+1><B>HOW DO WRITERS/PHOTOGRAPHERS MARKET THEIR WARES ON THEWWW? TWO EXCELLENT EXAMPLES:</B></FONT><P><CENTER></CENTER><P><B>1. MINDSTORE</B><BR>Hal Gieseking, former Consumer Editor of the Reader's Digest's Travel Holidaymagazine, past president of SATW, and author of 12 travel books, is mindingthe store all right. He has launched a new venture on the Internet: theMindstore: <A HREF="http://www.wmbg.com/mindstore">http://www.wmbg.com/mindstore</A>. The program offers courses onthe Internet of particular interest to writers and travel industry personnel.<BR><BR>One of these is a photography workshop conducted by Tom and Michele Grimm,world-trotting photographers whose color images have appeared in dozensof magazines. <BR><BR>The other is a course taught by Richard Janssen, former Senior Editor ofBusiness Week, called &quot;The Art of News Writing: Choosing and Schmoozing.&quot;The program could be of real help to anyone who has ever had to write afeature article for a newsletter or local newspaper or send out news releases,Hal tells us in his usual soft spoken manner. <BR><BR>Both courses begin with a free lesson to let Internet surfers decide ifthe course is for them. They can then purchase the balance of the coursefor $10 (photography workshop) or $15 (journalism course). But first, Halsuggests, check out those free lessons on the Internet! In case of emergencyhis email address is: hal@wmbg.com<BR><BR><B>2. WRITER/PHOTOGRAPHER LEE FOSTER , ONLINE A DOZEN YEARS ALREADY, JUSTKEEPS WINNING AWARDS</B><BR>Lee Foster, chairman of the Electronic Media Committee of SATW, has beennamed the 1996 winner of the Lowell Thomas award in the category of ElectronicComputer Media. This year the awards drew 1,041 entries from 518 individuals.Judging is by the faculty of the Medill School of Journalism at NorthwesternUniversity. <BR><BR>Lee has been publishing electronically since 1984 when his work startedappearing on CompuServe. He won the award this year for a cluster of 200articles available on his World Wide Web page <A HREF="http://www.forstertravel.com/">http://www.forstertravel.com</A>where surfers can sample a few items before subscribing at $25.00 per year.The same content is available on CompuServe where his features include WestCoast Travel (Go WCT to access), and Adventures in Travel (Go AIT). He alsopublishes a CD-ROM titled California Travel, with 50 of his texts and 650photos, available for $29.95. In the words of the award judges, &quot;Thewriting is lucid, always well-researched and notably reader-friendly.&quot;Typically he spends one week each month in the field gathering fresh material.Lee Foster can be reached at PO Box 5715, Berkeley, CA 94705; Phone/Fax510-549-2202; email at: lee@fostertravel.com or 76703,354@compuserve.com.<P><CENTER></CENTER><P><FONT size=+1><B>HEADLINE OF THE MONTH DEPARTMENT</B></FONT><BR>&quot;Sex Tourism Task Force Formed&quot; - headline on an August 29 pressrelease from the World Tourism Organization. <BR><BR>&quot;They sure won't have trouble getting volunteers,&quot; an industryfriend quips. <BR><BR>But this is very serious business. The headline refers to the just completedWorld Congress Against Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children. UNICEFestimates that there are up to one million children involved in prostitutionworldwide in a sex industry that often caters to tourists. A statement onthe Prevention of Organized Sex Tourism was adopted by the 120 nations attending.We or the WTO would be happy to provide a copy. <BR><BR>Nevertheless, if the purpose of a headline in part is to generate attentionand readership, in our opinion this one gets an A+. <P><CENTER></CENTER><P><FONT size=+1><B>YOUR NEWS AND COMMENTS WELCOME</B></FONT><BR>If you have news and comments to share with us and/or your fellow traveljournalists, just point and shoot us an email through the DANesbett linkbelow. We look forward to hearing from you. <BR><BR>DANesbett, Editor <BR><a href="mailto:dnesbett@travelleader.com">dnesbett@travelleader.com</a><br><BR>PS Be sure to register with us as travel journalists on the form provided,then enter the sweepstakes as often as you cruise the Travel Leader PR Newssite. <BR><BR>The current prize is a relaxing week for two (MAP) at the sybaritic SonestaBeach Resort and Casino Curacao, with R/T air provided by American Airlines...a prize that sure beats working. And good luck! <BR><A HREF="#top"><IMG SRC="up.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Up" WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="50" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" ALIGN=bottom></A><HR><A HREF="http://www.travelleader.com/butbar2.map"><IMG SRC="http://www.travelleader.com/tlsbutbr.gif" ISMAP BORDER="0" WIDTH="390"HEIGHT="78" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A><BR></BODY></HTML>
