<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>CLIA</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><FONT size=-1>Contact:<BR>Diana M. Orban Associates<BR>#104823<BR>(201) 605-2121</FONT> <BR><P><CENTER><FONT size=+2><B>WHERE CAN YOU GO ON A CRUISE?</B></FONT><BR>From Ashdod to Zanzibar, and (Nearly) All Points in Between </CENTER><P>In days of yore, sailors set out for ports undiscovered with little morethan a compass and some not-too-edible food. Luckily for today's cruisers,those days are long gone. <BR><BR>What isn't gone, though, is the sense of adventure that's awakened whenheaded for ports unknown. <BR><BR>From Ashdod in Israel to Zanzibar in Tanzania, and nearly all points inbetween, cruise ships are crisscrossing the globe and taking vacationersto more exotic and unusual destinations. And, with more than 1,800 portsof call worldwide, cruise vacationers are finding possibilities as diverseas the destinations themselves. <BR><BR>&quot;Have you ever thought of visiting Casablanca on a cruise? How aboutLatvia or Estonia?&quot; asks James G. Godsman, president of Cruise LinesInternational Association (CLIA). &quot;If you think you can't get thereby cruise ship, think again, because with more than 1,800 ports worldwide-- and countless land excursions offering a chance to explore a country'sinterior -- chances are you can.&quot; <BR><BR>&quot;And unlike our pioneering predecessors, you'll eat well, enjoy plushaccommodations, genuine relaxation and an exciting dose of fun,&quot; Godsmansays. <BR><BR><B>Not Your Usual Ports of Call </B><BR>Cruise vacationers seeking the unexpected will often find that they neednot venture too far from the ships, as cruise lines are punctuating theiritineraries with stops in exotic ports. Windstar Cruises, for example, stopsin Casablanca, the Moroccan city made famous by Humphrey Bogart, IngridBergman and Rick's American Cafe. Costa Cruise Lines takes passengers toDubrovnik, Croatia and Tallinn, Estonia. And, Seawind Cruise Line visitsGrenada, an island of soaring peaks covered with rain forests and dottedwith volcanic craters. <BR><BR>Radisson Seven Seas Cruises lists the Chilean fjords, the Russian Far Eastand both polar regions among its most unusual offerings, while CommodoreCruise Line takes vacationers to two Honduras ports, Puerto Cortes and RoatanIsland. In the winter, Royal Olympic Cruises' ships sail the Amazon Riverand the Straits of Magellan in South America, arriving in Rio de Janeiroin time for the spectacular Carnival celebrations. <BR><BR>Some of Crystal Cruises' itineraries include stops in Dubai, Arab EmirateRepublic; Moroni, Grande Comore Island; and Muscat, Oman, while Orient Linesstops in Ashdod, Madagascar, Antarctica, Zanzibar, Napier and Tasmania.<BR><BR>Fare, Huahine; Hiva Ov, Marquesas and Castro, Chiloe Island, Chile top thelist of unusual destinations offered by Seabourn Cruise Line, while PrincessCruises will offer, for the first time in 1997, stops in Mauritania; Aden,Aqaba; Orkney Islands; Latvia and Estonia. <BR><BR>Travelers interested in Central America can sail a partial transit of thePanama Canal with Regal Cruises, and on the way stop in Puerto Limon, CostaRica, where Christopher Columbus landed on his fourth voyage. And, Caribbeanfans also will find something unusual to see, as Carnival Cruise Lines offersits passengers a chance to visit the less-traveled ports of St. Lucia, St.Barts and St. Kitts. <BR><BR><B>Chock Full of Culture</B> <BR>For those travelers who would like to witness history in the making, SilverseaCruises offers its inaugural voyages to South Africa, where guests may witnessthe dramatic social changes taking place in this most beautiful and diverseof countries. Oceanic Cruises' August itineraries are timed to allow passengersa chance to go ashore for Japan's festivals. And those sailing with BergenLine, a newcomer to the CLIA fleet, will visit ports along Norway's westerncoast, including Alesund, known for its Art Nouveau architecture, and Trondheim,home of Nidaros Cathedral, where Norway's kings are coronated. <BR><BR>Passengers of Holland America Line will set foot in the Mayan ruins of Tikalin Guatemala and Copan in Honduras, while Cunard Line passengers will attenda party among the ancient ruins of Ephesus, in the Turkish fishing villageof Kusadasi. Cruisers looking to just kick back and relax may enjoy a day-longvisit at Royal Caribbean Cruise Line's private destinations, Labadee andCocoCay, or an afternoon stay at Taku Lodge, an Alaskan hideaway nestledamid glaciers, mountains and forests, when sailing with Celebrity Cruises.<BR><BR>Cruisers can also choose to get up close and personal with the natural phenomenaof an area. For example, when visiting Alaska with Norwegian Cruise Line,passengers on a hike can peer into and touch deep blue ice caves at MendenhallGlacier, and while sailing American Hawaii Cruises, vacationers get a super-closelook, from the deck, at the Kilauea Volcano as molten lava flows down thehillside and into the sea. <BR><BR>And, literary buffs sailing with Delta Queen Steamboat Co. may choose aside trip to The Cave, the Hannibal, Mo., boyhood home of Samuel Clemensand setting of the annual National Tom Sawyers Days Festival. <BR><BR>&quot;The sea has long intrigued travelers,&quot; says Godsman. &quot;Aslong as there are people, there will be craving for adventure and excitement,and as long as there's that, there will be a need to feel like a sailor,exploring ports unknown.&quot; <BR><BR>To learn more about the destinations accessible by cruise ship, contacta CLIA-affiliated travel agency near you. To find one, visit CLIA's homepageon the Internet, at (<a href="http://www.ten-io.com/clia/">http://www.ten-io.com/clia/</a>), or look for CLIA's blue,gold and white logo in local travel agents' windows. <BR><BR>September 1996 <BR><BR>NOTE TO EDITORS: A copy of Cruise Lines International Association's Guideto Worldwide Destinations is available to editors only by calling (201)605-2121. <BR><BR>A booklet that includes CLIA's &quot;destinations grid&quot;</BODY></HTML><center><a href="http://www.travelleader.com/butbar2.map"><IMG SRC="http://www.travelleader.com/tlsbutbr.gif" ISMAP border=0 WIDTH="390" HEIGHT="78" ALIGN=bottom></a></center></body></html>
