<DOCNO>WT06-B09-142</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA045-000810-B026-88</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.travelleader.com:80/tlpr/belgian/comics.html 204.249.214.30 19970118221324 text/html 2858
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 18 Jan 1997 22:12:24 GMT
Server: Apache/1.0.0
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 2687
Last-modified: Wed, 23 Oct 1996 21:32:45 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<body>
<font size=4>

<center><img src="belgian2.gif" border=0></center>

<br><b>Contact:</b>
<dl><dd>Liliane Menin-Opsomer
<dd>Press and Public Relations Manager
<dd>e-mail: <a href="mailto:belpress@nyfer.blythe.org"> belpress@nyfer.blythe.org</a>
</dl>

<p><center><b>100th Anniversary of Comic Strip Art - A year long event</center></b>

<p>Belgium may not be the birthplace, but it is definitely the cradle of the Comic Book.

<p>On 18 October 1896 a new form of art was born, when the Yellow Kid by Richard F. Outcault appeared in the New York Journal. This was the birth of comic strip art. For the first time the typical division into separate pictures was used for telling a story.  For the first time too, the speech balloon was used systematically to contain the dialogues.

<p>This editorial novelty came to Belgium only in 1929 with the creation of the comic strip character Tintin and was soon followed by Spirou, Lucky Luke and the Smurfs just to name a few.

<p>Belgium turned out to be an exceptionally fertile breeding ground for comic strip art.  Not only did the 9th Art thrive in our country - which it still does - but a whole comic strip culture has come into being. The most prestigious bookshops offer all kinds of comics, there are Tintin shops and comic strip book even has an influence on fashion, advertising and many other areas involving merchandising.

<p>The centenary of the comic strip art will therefore not go by silently.  There will be no single day on which the comic strip art lover will not be able to choose from a wide range of exhibitions throughout Belgium.  Center stage will be occupied by the Belgian Center for Comic Strip Art in Brussels,  a museum entirely dedicated to the 9th Art.     Herewith a selection of exhibitions:

<ul>
<li>Willy, Wanda and Fauna at the Antwerp Zoo from May through September 1996

<pre>
</pre><li>50 Years of Lucky Luke at the Center for Comic Strip Art in Brussels from June 4th through October 6th

<pre>
</pre><li>The traditional Meybom (planting of the tree) festivities in Brussels with a parade of giant comic strip art characters present on August 9th 1996
</ul>

<p>For more information contact : The Belgian Center for Comic Strip Art, 20 rue des Sables, 1000 Brussels.  Open every day from 10 am to 6 pm. Closed on Mondays and January 1, November 1 and December 25.
<br>Tel: 011 32 2/219.19.80 Fax: 011 32 2/219.23.76

<p>Hotels join the celebrations and offer special Comic Strip Art Weekends. For information and a complete calendar of events celebrating the 100th Anniversary of Comic Strip Art contact the Belgian Tourist Office in New York.
</body>
</html>
