<head><title>Litchfield</title></head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<font size=-1>
CONTACT:<br>
Annette Bartle<br>
(212) 288-3838<br>
Janet L. Serra<br>
(860) 567-4506</font>
<p>
<center><font size=+2>A spectacular meal and a spectacular view, all in one! 
In the rural Litchfield Hills nature provides an extravaganza of autumn colors as visitors enjoy gourmet meals in quaint country inns.</font></center>
<p>
LITCHFIELD, CT  --  Brilliantly hued autumn leaves provide a magnificent background for diners enjoying a meal in one of many Litchfield Hills country inns.  Terraces and porches look to scenic rivers and landscapes ablaze with a thousand shades of Autumn in this northwestern corner of the Nutmeg State where the prized broad leaved trees abound.
<p>
The Old Riverton Inn, Route 20, Riverton, CT. 860-379-8678 sits on the west branch of the Farmington River.  Listed on the National Register of Historic Places, and meticulously restored over the years, this friendly establishment has been pleasing visitors since it first opened exactly 200 years ago.  A Sunday dinner on the Grindstone Terrace may feature Chef Roy's Boneless Breast of Chicken with Sauce Barnaise and Almonds.
<p>
In the rural, tranquil setting by the Bantam River, The Stone House Cafe and Gallery, 637 Bantam Road, Rte. 202, Litchfield, CT; 860-567-3326 is a historic two-story structure that was once part of a farm.  Guests can have their meal on a patio above the river.  Among often requested specialties are the Stone House Crabcakes, served with a sweet-hot Thai Chili sauce.
<p>
The rustic Tributary Restaurant, On the River, Winsted, CT; 860-379-7679 was once known as the "Old Barn on Rowley Street".  Built in 1861 and carefully renovated, its interior bricks come from a torn-down jail.  Gourmets from near and far come to savor the Tributary Bouillabaisse, seafood simmered in a tomato broth, white wine, leeks, fennel and a touch of saffron over linguini.  The Brookside Bistro in West Cornwall, 860-672-6601 is steps away from the historic covered bridge on the Housatonic River, one of just two in Connecticut that can be crossed by car.  Lamb shank braised with white beans and red cabbage is a Bistro favorite served on the spacious screened porch that perches above a lively stream.
<p>
To find out more about autumn dining and other happenings in the Litchfield Hills and to get a free 40 page brochure of what to see and do in the area, overnight accommodations, dining, shopping and just having fun, contact:  The Litchfield Hills Travel Council, P.O. Box 968J, Litchfield, CT 06759; Phone: 860-567-4506; Fax: 860-567-5214.
<p>
