<html><head><title>TIA</title></head><body bgcolor="ffffff"><font size=-1>DATE:<br>March 7, 1996<br>CONTACT:<br>Dexter Koehl<br>Shawn Flaherty<br>(202) 408-2137</font><p><center><font size=+2>STATE TOURISM BUDGETSGROW MODESTLY</font></center><p>WASHINGTON, DC--State governments* plan to spend $413 million for travel and tourism development and promotion in fiscal year 1995-96, according to the Travel Industry Association  of America's 1995-96 Survey of State Travel Offices.  The 1995-96 figure is up 2.5 percent compared to fiscal year 1994-95.  <p>"This may seem like the battle of the big budgets, but it really is a battle for the big bucks.  Travel and tourism generates a huge return on investment---so these states are anteing up.  For a majority, the travel industry is their first, second, or third largest employer, and a major source of new jobs," explained TIA President & CEO William S. Norman.<p>The importance of travel to state economies is also reflected in the dramatic increase in state travel office budgets evident over the longer-term.  For example, in 1984-85, all 50 state travel budgets totaled $189 million--less than half of this year's $413 million. <p>The 1995-96 Survey of State Travel Offices provides comprehensive data on state travel office operations and is intended as an informational guide for state travel directors, as well as those in private industry. The survey presents a categoric breakdown of both the projected budgets for fiscal year 1995-96, as well as the actual expenditures for fiscal year 1994-95.<p>Illinois, with a budget of $31.5 million, bumped Hawaii out of first place in terms of size of total tourism budget.  Hawaii's budget was slashed 21 percent from FY 1994-95. Maryland  recorded the largest increase in its overall budget, rising 74 percent to $8.9 million.  Conversely, Washington state experienced the largest drop, declining 49 percent. The average budget for state travel offices is $8.5 million.<p>A considerable amount of each state's travel office budget is allocated for advertising purposes.  Texas takes the lead in advertising, budgeting $9 million for 1995-96.  The total advertising budget for all states* is $110 million, up 5.3 percent.  The average advertising budget for 1995-96 is $2.5 million.<p>The 1995-96 Survey of State Travel Offices is available for $475 through the TIA membership department at (202) 408-TIAA.<p><font size=-1>* Colorado is not included in these figures since voters in 1994 rejected a two-tenths of a percent tax hike to fund the Colorado Tourism Board's operation.  As a result, Colorado is now the only state without a government-funded tourism office to help market their product.</font><p><hr><p>TIA is the national, non-profit association representing all components of the $430 billion U.S. travel industry.  TIA's mission is to promote and facilitate travel to and within the United States.<p><center><a href="http://www.travelleader.com/butbar2.map"><IMG SRC="http://www.travelleader.com/tlsbutbr.gif" ISMAP border=0 WIDTH="390" HEIGHT="78" ALIGN=bottom></a></center></body></html>
